# Add LECTURE DISPLAY MODE to an SR shell sim

You are adding one small feature to a single already-converted SR shell sim
(`*-shell.html`). It already has `#shell` with `shell-header`/`shell-aside`, the
guided-inquiry stepper (`#aside-inquiry`, `#inq-cards`, `#aside-inquiry-restore`),
and a `Shell = (function(){…})()` runtime that owns the stepper.

**The feature:** a header button **`🎓 Lecture`**, placed right after the theme
button, that toggles a *lecture display mode*:
- **ON:** hide the guided inquiry (collapse it to the existing `▸ Guided inquiry`
  restore bar) AND advance the sim to its **complete state** — the exact scene a
  student sees after clicking *Finish* on the last card.
- **OFF** (second click on the button, OR clicking the restore bar): re-open the
  guided inquiry and **re-initiate it from step 1**.

It also **removes the old `Skip ✕` button** — the header Lecture button now owns
the "hide the inquiry" affordance.

## THE #1 RULE — do not touch the science, visuals, or controls
- **NEVER change physics, numerical methods, draw/render functions, equations,
  constants, or canvas visuals.** Byte-for-byte identical.
- **Do not change what controls/readouts exist or what they do.**
- **Do not edit `simulation-shell.css`.** No CSS changes are needed — the button
  reuses `.shell-btn` and the existing `.active` state; hiding the inquiry reuses
  the existing `inquiry-collapsed` machinery.
- This is a **surgical, anchor-based edit of one HTML file.** Do NOT swap the whole
  `Shell` runtime block — the runtime has drifted slightly between sims, so only
  make the four targeted changes below and leave every other runtime line as-is.

## Why this is safe / how it works (read once)
- The runtime already has `setInquiryCollapsed(on)` (hides the inquiry to the
  restore bar) and `inqShow(n)` (sets the step, updates dots, **and calls
  `onStep(n)`** which repaints the scene).
- Every sim's `onStep(i)` is idempotent — the scene is a pure function of the step
  index (`onStep(i)` → `setStage(…)`/`applyInquiryStep(i)` → `draw()`). So the
  "complete, post-Finish scene" is reached by jumping to the **last** step:
  `inqShow(lastIndex)`.
- **If (and only if) a specific sim's `onStep` turns out to be *incremental*** (a
  one-time delta per step rather than state = f(step)) and jumping to the last step
  does NOT show the full scene, use the fallback in Edit 2's note (replay all
  steps). Verify by comparing against a real click-through-and-Finish.

